### Document Summary

This document is an "IBM Batch Report" for Batch Number 17 from the Bangor Vote Collection Point (ID 2178) in NSW, created on June 10, 2016, and reported on June 15, 2016. It details the processing of 50 ballots for Electoral Event ID 19694. The report includes batch-level metadata such as operator, workstation, and site. For each of the 50 individual ballots, the document provides the outcome of various processing checks, including:

*   Quality Assurance
*   Initials and Official Mark verification
*   Unusual Markings assessment
*   Formality Result and Reason
*   Verification Action taken
*   Above-the-Line (ATL) preferences (checked, mismatches, saved, breakdown, and formal status)
*   Below-the-Line (BTL) preferences (checked, mismatches, saved, breakdown, and formal status)

Crucially, all 50 ballots recorded in this report show an "OK" status across all processing checks, indicating that no issues or anomalies were detected for any ballot in this batch.

### Relevance to FOI Request

This document is directly relevant to Vanessa Teague's FOI request [LEX540] as it is one of the "IBM Batch Report" PDF files from June 2016, providing granular detail on ballot processing. It falls within the requested scope of documents categorized by Vote Collection Point ("Bangor") and Batch Number ("17"). The report fulfills the request's stated objective of yielding insights into ballot processing, including batch metadata, electoral event context, and specific ballot-level checks for formality, initials, marks, and preferences (ATL/BTL).

While the FOI request overview highlights that many "IBM Batch Report" files frequently show "HAS ISSUES" entries for specific checks (e.g., `UnusualMarkings Checked`, `Verification Action`, `ATL Mismatches`), this particular document represents a batch where all recorded checks for all 50 ballots resulted in "OK." This provides a contrasting example within the dataset, illustrating a batch that apparently processed without any identified exceptions or anomalies requiring specific attention.
